<h2>Finding 5: Organic CTR Drops 58% When AI Overviews Appear</h2>
<p><strong>Background:</strong> Click-through rate measures how often searchers click on a result. Higher CTR means more traffic to your website.</p>
<p><strong>Results:</strong> Ahrefs analyzed 300,000+ keywords and found that AI Overviews reduce the organic <a href="/glossary/click-through-rate/">click-through rate</a> for position-1 content by 58%. Seer Interactive's study of 68,000 real queries found an even steeper decline: organic CTR dropped from 1.76% to 0.61%, a 65% reduction. Position-1 CTR fell from 7.3% in March 2024 to 2.6% in March 2025.</p>
<p><strong>Context:</strong> A 58% CTR drop does not mean 58% less traffic across all queries. AI Overviews appear on about 1 in 4 searches. The impact concentrates on informational and "near me" queries where AI summaries satisfy the user without a click. Transactional queries with high purchase intent still drive clicks to organic results. The strategy is to <a href="/blog/ai-overview-optimization/">optimize for AI citations</a> rather than fight the format. Businesses cited inside AI Overviews see 35% higher CTR than non-cited competitors.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Organic CTR impact when AI Overviews appear" src="/images/blog/ai-overviews-ctr-impact-local.webp" /></p>
<h2>Finding 6: Users Are 47% Less Likely to Click With AI Overviews Present</h2>
<p><strong>Background:</strong> AI Overviews aim to answer the query directly on the search results page. This changes user behavior in measurable ways.</p>
<p><strong>Results:</strong> Users are 47% less likely to click any traditional search result when an AI Overview displays. Search sessions end 26% of the time when AI summaries are present, compared to only 16% for standard result pages. Only 1% of users clicked links within the AI summaries themselves in Q1 2025.</p>
<p><strong>Context:</strong> The 1% in-summary click rate is a critical number. It means AI Overviews do not drive referral traffic. They absorb attention and satisfy queries. For local businesses, this creates a zero-click problem. A searcher asks "best dentist in Austin" and reads the AI summary without visiting any website. The businesses mentioned in the summary gain brand awareness. The businesses not mentioned gain nothing. Building <a href="/blog/eeat-google-quality-guide/">E-E-A-T signals</a> and earning AI citations becomes the new organic strategy.</p>
<h2>Finding 7: Local Pack Ads Grew From 1% to 22% of Mobile Results</h2>
<p><strong>Background:</strong> Google monetizes local search through ads placed inside local packs and Local Services Ads (LSAs). As organic visibility shrinks, paid placement expands.</p>
<p><strong>Results:</strong> Local pack ads appeared in just 1% of mobile local search results in January 2025. By January 2026, that figure reached 22%. Local Services Ads now appear on 31% of tracked queries, up from 11% in early 2025. This represents a 182% increase in LSA visibility in 12 months.</p>
<p><strong>Context:</strong> Google is shifting local search toward a pay-to-play model. As AI Overviews reduce organic clicks, ad inventory fills the gap. Businesses that previously relied on free organic visibility through their <a href="/blog/gbp-statistics-2026/">Google Business Profile</a> now face a choice: invest in ads or invest in content that earns AI citations. Both paths require budget. The difference is that content compounds over time while ads stop the moment you stop paying. A <a href="/blog/local-seo-statistics/">local SEO strategy</a> that combines GBP optimization, local content, and selective ad spend outperforms either approach alone.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Local pack ad growth from January 2025 to January 2026" src="/images/blog/local-pack-ad-growth-2025-2026.webp" /></p>
<h2>Finding 8: Cited Businesses Earn 35% Higher Organic CTR</h2>
<p><strong>Background:</strong> Not all AI Overview impact is negative. Businesses that earn citations inside AI summaries see the opposite effect.</p>
<p><strong>Results:</strong> Businesses cited in AI Overviews earn 35% higher organic CTR on the same queries. Paid CTR for cited businesses increases 91%. Pages that appear as sources in AI summaries benefit from the "authority halo" effect. Google treats citation-worthy content as a ranking signal for traditional results as well.</p>
<p><strong>Context:</strong> The path to AI citation mirrors traditional <a href="/blog/seo-for-beginners/">SEO best practices</a> but with higher standards. Google AI selects sources based on content depth, factual accuracy, <a href="/blog/structured-data-guide/">structured data markup</a>, and E-E-A-T signals. Thin service pages with 200 words do not earn citations. Detailed guides, data-driven content, and original research do. Local businesses that publish authoritative content about their industry and service area earn citations at higher rates. This is the <a href="/blog/how-many-blog-posts-to-rank/">content compound effect</a> in action.</p>
